## Pre-existing editorial drift ‚Äî context only, NOT gated (parked)
The committed `specmap.json` is stale vs the tree (the drift M1 would catch):
- unbumped-hash (content changed, revision still r1) on 9 anchors:
  `PROP-024#bootstrap`, `PROP-024#placement`, `PROP-002#registry-model`,
  `PROP-008#collision`, `PROP-008#migration`, `PROP-008#pkgref`,
  `PROP-008#repo-naming`, `PROP-008#short-name`, `PROP-007#path-source`.
- vs committed json: units +98, edges +14/‚àí8.
This drift is orthogonal to dangling. It is NOT part of gate 1 and is not resolved
here (respecting the park).

## Gate-1 procedure (run per capsule, ¬ß4.9.1)
1. **Primary (precise, cheap):** for every address the capsule moves, grep the code
   for citers of the OLD address ‚Äî
   `grep -rEn '#\[spec|#\[verifies|scope!' crates/ xtask/ | grep '<old#anchor>'`
   (or grep the raw old address). Every code citer must be retargeted to the new
   address. Prose citers are handled via `prose-links.tsv` (gate 2).
2. **Secondary (whole-graph):** run `cargo xtask specmap`; assert the summary is
   still `‚Ä¶ 0 suspects, 0 warnings` and the ratchet still reports **exactly** the
   one known orphan (no NEW suspect/warning/orphan). Then `git checkout -- specmap.json`
   to keep the committed index at its parked baseline.
3. A growth in suspects/warnings, or a NEW orphan, = a severed edge ‚Üí the capsule
   fails gate 1; fix before committing.

## Companion baseline files
- `prose-links.tsv` ‚Äî 121 `spec://` prose citations across 69 corpus files (gate 2:
  no NEW broken prose link ‚Äî every citation still resolves to an existing anchor).
- `anchors.tsv` ‚Äî 729 `{#anchor}` definitions across the corpus (the resolution
  target set; a moved anchor keeps its `{#‚Ä¶}`, so its identity survives the move).
